| name               = Jens Lehmann\n| image              = Jens Lehmann - 2019202184453 2019-07-21 Champions for Charity - 3017 - B70I3052 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Lehmann in 2019\n| fullname           = Jens Gerhard Lehmann<ref name=\"FIFA\">{{Cite web |title=FIFA World Cup Germany 2006 \u2013 List of Players |url=http://www.fifadata.com/document/fwc/2006/PDF/FWC_2006_SquadLists.pdf |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) |format=PDF |page=12 |accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n| height             = 1.90 m<ref name=\"FIFA\"/>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1969|11|10|df=y}}<ref name=\"FIFA\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[Essen]], West Germany\n| position           = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub        = [[FC Augsburg]] (assistant coach)\n| youthyears1        = | youthclubs1 =\n| years1             = 1988\u20131998 |clubs1 = [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] |caps1 = 274 |goals1 = 2\n| years2             = 1998\u20131999 |clubs2 = [[A.C. Milan]]               |caps2 = 5   |goals2 = 0\n| years3             = 1999\u20132003 |clubs3 = [[Borussia Dortmund]]        |caps3 = 129 |goals3 = 0\n| years4             = 2003\u20132008 |clubs4 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]     |caps4 = 147 |goals4 = 0\n| years5             = 2008\u20132010 |clubs5 = [[VfB Stuttgart]]            |caps5 = 65  |goals5 = 0\n| years6             = 2011      |clubs6 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]     |caps6 = 1   |goals6 = 0\n| totalcaps          = 622       | totalgoals = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 1989\u20131990 |nationalteam1 = [[Germany national under-21 football team|West Germany U21]] |nationalcaps1 = 6 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1998\u20132008 |nationalteam2 = [[Germany national football team|Germany]] |nationalcaps2 = 61 |nationalgoals2 = 0\n| medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fb|GER}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 Japan\u2013South Korea]]|}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 Germany]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[UEFA Euro 2008|2008 Austria-Switzerland]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup|2005 Germany]]|}}\n}}\n'''Jens Gerhard Lehmann''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8j\u025bns \u02c8le\u02d0man|pron}};<ref>{{cite book |first=Max |last=Mangold |title=Aussprachew\u00f6rterbuch |language=German |year=2005 |publisher=Dudenverlag |edition=6th |location=Mannheim |isbn=9783411040667 |pp=441 and 504}}</ref> born 10 November 1969) is a retired German [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].\n\nHe was voted UEFA Club Goalkeeper of the Year for the 1996\u201397 and 2005\u201306 seasons, and was selected for three [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] squads. He was a member of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]'s [[The Invincibles (football)#Arsenal|'Invincibles']], playing every match of their unbeaten title-winning season in 2003\u201304. He also holds the [[UEFA Champions League]] record for the most consecutive [[clean sheets]], not conceding a single goal in 10 consecutive matches while he played for Arsenal.\n\n==Club career==\n===Schalke 04===\nLehmann started his career in the 1988\u201389 season<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rsssf.com/players/jlehmanndata.html |title=Jens Lehmann - Matches and Goals in Bundesliga |first=Matthias |last=Arnhold |date=1 October 2015 |accessdate=12 November 2015 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref> with [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]], playing for them for nearly a decade. His first years were rocky, notably a game against [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] in 1993 in which he conceded three goals and was substituted after 45 minutes,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/bundesliga/1994/12/leverkusen-schalke/ |title=Bayer Leverkusen - FC Schalke 04 |accessdate=30 November 2007 |language=German |publisher=fussballdaten.de}}</ref> causing him to flee the stadium alone by tram rather than taking the team bus,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faz.net/s/Rub47986C2FBFBD461B8A2C1EC681AD639D/Doc~E336A733D0AD84679B26B9D3C9EEA71AD~ATpl~Ecommon~Scontent.html |title=Vom Libero zum Titan? |accessdate=30 November 2007 |language=German |work=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung |date=8 June 2006 |author=Peter He\u00df}}</ref> but Lehmann gradually established himself as a strong keeper lauded for his ability to intercept crosses.\n\nHe scored his first league goal on 12 March 1995 in a 6\u20132 victory over [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen|1860 Munich]] in the 84th minute, scoring Schalke's sixth goal from the penalty spot.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/bundesliga/1995/21/schalke-1860muenchen/ |title=FC Schalke 04 - TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen |accessdate=30 November 2007 |language=German |publisher=fussballdaten.de}}</ref> His second goal was a last-minute equaliser scored against bitter rivals, Borussia Dortmund, in the [[Revierderby]] on 19 December 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fussballdaten.de/bundesliga/1998/20/dortmund-schalke/ |title=Borussia Dortmund \u2013 FC Schalke 04 |accessdate=30 November 2007 |language=German |publisher=fussballdaten.de}}</ref>\n\nLehmann became Schalke's team hero in their [[1997 UEFA Cup Final]] victory over [[Inter Milan]], after playing a strong season and saving an [[Iv\u00e1n Zamorano]] penalty in a [[penalty shootout (football)|penalty shootout]].\n\n===A.C. Milan===\nLehmann left Schalke for [[A.C. Milan]] in 1998, but his performances were below par. In one game [[Gabriel Batistuta]] scored a hat-trick against him, including a goal from a free kick in the box which Lehmann had conceded by handling a back pass.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kZxwEkZvAwQ |title=Batistuta Free Kick |accessdate=15 September 2006 |publisher=YouTube |date=23 September 2009}}</ref> In another game he was substituted after giving away a penalty.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/sep/30/teams-punished-defeats-football-questions |title=Which teams have been punished for defeats? |work=The Guardian |accessdate=27 January 2010 |location=London |first=John |last=Ashdown |date=30 September 2009}}</ref> After just five matches, Lehmann was dropped. Believing he wouldn't get another chance at Milan, he left during the winter.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calciomercato/storie/23-06-2019/abbagli-estivi-delapena-lehmann-meteora-blanchard-peggiori-acquisti-mercato-98-99-340304745865/jens-lehmann-milan.shtml |title=De La Pe\u00f1a, Lehmann e la meteora Blanchard: i peggiori acquisti del mercato '98-'99 |work=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |last1=Guidi |first1=Marco |date=12 July 2017 |accessdate=12 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Borussia Dortmund===\nIn early 1999, Lehmann returned to Germany to play for [[Borussia Dortmund]] replacing long-time goalkeeper [[Stefan Klos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://skladyfutbol.pl/infopage.php?id=1179|publisher = Skladyfutbol.pl|title=Borussia Dortmund 1998-99|date=10 February 2020|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref> Lehmann had a difficult start there after several poor performances. Rumors arose that Lehmann might leave, with supporters viewing him critically.\n\nBut the tide eventually turned and Lehmann's form improved, becoming a reliable figure in the team. He played a significant part in the club's return to the upper echelons of German and European football. Borussia Dortmund began the 2001\u201302 season strongly and eventually won the [[Bundesliga]] in [[2001\u201302 Bundesliga|2001\u201302]]. That same year, Borussia Dortmund reached the UEFA-Cup final, though the team lost to Dutch club Feyenoord Rotterdam.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rsssf.com/players/lehmann-in-ec.html |title=Jens Lehmann - Matches in European Cups |first=Marcel |last=Haisma |date=15 January 2010 |accessdate=12 November 2015 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, Lehmann developed a reputation for his poor disciplinary record. In a match against [[SC Freiburg]], Lehmann kicked opposing attacker [[Soumaila Coulibaly]] after they collided in the penalty area. Lehmann was suspended afterwards. He currently holds the record for most red cards for any Borussia Dortmund player, and the record for most red cards for a goalkeeper in the German Bundesliga.\n\nLehmann's form slipped in the 2002\u201303 season, along with Borussia Dortmund's. His time at Dortmund was winding down, and after the season concluded, he left Dortmund. He was replaced by [[Roman Weidenfeller]] and [[Guillaume Warmuz]], who had just left Arsenal.\n\n===Arsenal===\n====2003\u201304 season====\nLehmann joined [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 25 July 2003 replacing the recently departed [[David Seaman]]. Arsenal's 2003\u201304 season was historic. The Gunners finished the [[2003\u201304 FA Premier League]] season unbeaten, becoming the first English club to accomplish the feat in the modern era and only the second to ever have an unbeaten season in English football's top tier, the only other team to accomplish this feat being [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in the 1888\u201389 season. Lehmann played every match in Arsenal's unbeaten season, though his swashbuckling playing style did lead to occasional mistakes. For example, in the title-winning match at local rivals [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], Lehmann pushed Tottenham striker [[Robbie Keane]] as the pair waited for a Tottenham corner.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3628573.stm |title=Arsenal clinch title |accessdate=30 November 2007 |work=BBC Sport |date=25 April 2004}}</ref> He also committed an error that led to the equalising goal in Arsenal's Champions League defeat at home to Chelsea the same season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,2144,1166223,00.html |title=Hot-headed German Goalie Faces London Bench |accessdate=30 November 2007 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=9 April 2004}}</ref> Despite these mistakes, Lehmann's addition to the Arsenal team had a major effect on Arsenal's ability to finish unbeaten. And Arsenal continued unbeaten until 24 October 2004. At the end of his first season at Arsenal, he had already played 54 times earning himself a [[Premier League]] winners medal.\n\n====2004\u201305 season====\nBy the middle of the [[2004-05 in English football|2004\u201305]] season, Lehmann's inconsistent form lead to Spaniard [[Manuel Almunia]] starting in several matches instead. However, Almunia made a series of mistakes during several games, thus allowing Lehmann to regain his position. At the end of that season, as speculation again began to mount that he would be replaced over the summer, Lehmann cemented his position in the Arsenal goal with a man-of-the-match performance against Manchester United in the 2005 [[FA Cup]] final. He made several important saves and demonstrated great positional sense to keep the score 0\u20130 after [[extra time]], and then crucially saved [[Paul Scholes]]' shot in the penalty shootout, which Arsenal won 5\u20134.\n\n====2005\u201306 season====\nLehmann had an outstanding [[2005-06 in English football|2005\u201306 season]] with Arsenal, making his 100th Premier League appearance for the club in their game against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 15 April 2006. He was a key factor in his side's first-ever accession to the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] final; during their run Arsenal broke the record for the most consecutive [[Shutout|clean sheets]] in the Champions League with ten, breaking the record of seven that Milan had set just one year before. That run formed the bulk of an 853-minute spell without conceding a goal, overtaking the CL record for an individual goalkeeper set by [[Edwin van der Sar]].\n\n[[Bayern Munich]]'s [[Hasan Salihamid\u017ei\u0107]] had been the last to net against Lehmann, in the 64th minute of a last 16 first leg match on 22 February 2005; Lehmann kept a clean sheet in the second leg, and then a further seven during Arsenal's run in 2005\u201306 (Almunia played in the other five matches in the group stages). The final clean sheet was earned in the semi-finals against [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]], after Lehmann saved an 89th minute [[Juan Rom\u00e1n Riquelme]] penalty. Lehmann maintained his shutout run despite an ignominious end to his [[2006 UEFA Champions League Final]] against [[FC Barcelona]]; with the score still at 0\u20130 he was sent off in the 18th minute for a [[professional foul]] after bringing down [[Samuel Eto'o]], making him the first player and only goalkeeper to ever be sent off in a Champions League/European Cup final, but it did not stop him from being named the Champions League Goalkeeper of the Year for the 2005\u201306 season after going 853 minutes without conceding a goal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/arsenal/article1706542.ece |location=London |work=The Times |first=Matt |last=Hughes |title=Lehmann to sign new contract |date=26 April 2007}}</ref>\n[[File:Jens Lehmann dive.JPG|thumb|250px|Lehmann diving to save a shot during a warm-up.]]\n\n====2006\u201307 season====\nHis remarkable run was finally ended on 13 September 2006 by [[Hamburger SV]]'s [[Boubacar Sanogo]], who scored a consolation goal in the 89th minute of Arsenal's first group stage match of the [[UEFA Champions League 2006-07|2006\u201307]] Champions League season.\n\nLehmann's contract at Arsenal was due to expire in summer 2007 and during the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]] season there was much speculation he would leave the club on a [[Bosman ruling|Bosman]] transfer. However, it was reported on 26 April 2007 that he had signed a year's extension on his contract, tying him to the club until 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/6594633.stm |title=Lehmann pens new Arsenal contract |accessdate=30 November 2007 |work=BBC Sport |date=27 April 2007}}</ref>\n\n====2007\u201308 season====\nIn the first league game of the 2007\u201308 season, Lehmann made a serious error after just 52 seconds, allowing [[David Healy (footballer)|David Healy]] to score for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]. However, Lehmann's blushes were spared late in the game as Arsenal won 2\u20131. In his second league match against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] he fumbled a [[David Dunn]] shot to allow Blackburn to equalise, in a game that finished 1\u20131. On 24 August, the BBC reported that he returned to Germany to treat an [[Achilles tendon]] injury which he picked up during international duty against [[England national football team|England]], meaning [[Manuel Almunia]] took his place for Arsenal's third match.\n\nLehmann subsequently had to wait nearly four months to make another competitive appearance for Arsenal, which came in their final Champions League group match against [[FC Steaua Bucure\u015fti|Steaua Bucharest]]. Nearly one month later, he played only his fifth competitive game of the season for Arsenal, against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in the third round of the [[FA Cup]]; meanwhile third-choice goalkeeper [[\u0141ukasz Fabia\u0144ski]] was selected for the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] games. Lehmann expressed frustration at being number two to Manuel Almunia<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/arsenal/article3078642.ece |title=Jens Lehmann angry with secondary role |accessdate=5 January 2008 |date=20 December 2007 |work=The Times |location=London}}</ref> fearing it could cost him the number one jersey in the German national team for the European Championship 2008. However, Arsenal manager Ars\u00e8ne Wenger described Lehmann's attitude as \u201csuper-professional\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2329634/Jens-Lehmann-calls-the-shots-on-Arsenal-future.html |title=Jens Lehmann calls the shots on Arsenal future |accessdate=21 February 2014 |date=28 December 2007 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |first1=Steve |last1=Wilson}}</ref>\n[[File:Jens Lehmann.jpg|left|thumb|185px|Lehmann playing for Arsenal in 2007.]]\nOn 26 January 2008, Lehmann appeared in Arsenal's second FA Cup game of the season, keeping his second successive clean sheet as Arsenal beat [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] 3\u20130. Manager Ars\u00e8ne Wenger later promised Lehmann that, if he stayed at Arsenal, he would play every game in the FA Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arsenal.com/article.asp?thisNav=first+team&article=486865&lid=&Title=Wenger+-+I%27ve+promised+Lehmann+FA+Cup+ties |title=Wenger \u2013 I've promised Lehmann FA Cup ties |accessdate=28 January 2008 |date=28 January 2008 |publisher=Arsenal.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080417013824/http://www.arsenal.com/article.asp?thisNav=first+team&article=486865&lid=&Title=Wenger+-+I%27ve+promised+Lehmann+FA+Cup+ties |archivedate=17 April 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On 29 January 2008, Lehmann suggested that he will stick with Arsenal until his contract expires at the end of the season. Lehmann gave his reasons as his relationship with the fans, players, family situations and his chance to still be able to win things at the club; believing he \"wouldn\u2019t have had this chance somewhere else.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arsenal.com/article.asp?thisNav=News&article=486905&lid=NewsHeadline&Title=Lehmann+-+I+think+I+have+a+chance+to+win+things |title=Lehmann - I think I have a chance to win things |accessdate=29 January 2008 |date=29 January 2008 |publisher=Arsenal.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080131161303/http://www.arsenal.com/article.asp?thisNav=News&article=486905&lid=NewsHeadline&Title=Lehmann+-+I+think+I+have+a+chance+to+win+things |archivedate=31 January 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On 2 February 2008, following an injury to Almunia, Lehmann returned in goal for Arsenal in the Premiership for an away fixture against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], more than five months after his last league appearance; Arsenal won the match 3\u20131. Due to Almunia catching flu straight after the injury, Lehmann kept his place in goal for the following three matches in February, including the first leg of the UEFA Champions League round of 16 against Milan, but also the 4\u20130 loss to arch rivals Manchester United in the FA Cup.\n\nAfter another injury to Almunia in early April 2008, Lehmann was back in goal for the away game against Manchester United on 13 April 2008. Arsenal lost that game 2\u20131, virtually ending their Premier League title hopes for the season, their third consecutive season without a major trophy. There was speculation that would be his last game for Arsenal, but on 19 April Lehmann played in the home game against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], which Arsenal won 2\u20130. The following week, \u0141ukasz Fabia\u0144ski was given his Premier League debut against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and Almunia returned to the bench for the game. However, Lehmann made another appearance and was brought on for Fabia\u0144ski in the last 20 minutes of the game against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 4 May 2008, Arsenal's final home game of the season. He was given a standing ovation after the match as he bowed and clapped to the fans. Later that day, Wenger confirmed that it was Lehmann's farewell appearance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arsenal.com/article.asp?thisNav=News&article=490968&lid=NewsHeadline&Title=Wenger:+%27You+could+see+it+was+an+end+of+season+game%27 |title=Wenger: 'You could see it was an end of season game' |accessdate=5 May 2008 |date=4 May 2008 |publisher=Arsenal.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508210608/http://www.arsenal.com/article.asp?thisNav=News&article=490968&lid=NewsHeadline&Title=Wenger%3A+%27You+could+see+it+was+an+end+of+season+game%27 |archivedate=8 May 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===VfB Stuttgart===\nIn early June 2008, it was announced that Lehmann had signed a one-year contract for [[VfB Stuttgart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vfb.de/archiv/en/aktuell/news/2007/22056.php| archive-url=https://archive.is/20140222000921/http://www.vfb.de/archiv/en/aktuell/news/2007/22056.php| url-status=dead| archive-date=22 February 2014 |title=Jens Lehmann signs for VfB |publisher=vfb.de |accessdate=21 February 2014 |date=3 June 2008}}</ref> He joined the team's pre-season training on 24 July 2008,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vfb.de/en/aktuell/news/2008/24466.php |title=All eyes on Lehmann |publisher=vfb.de |accessdate=30 July 2008 |date=24 July 2008}} {{Dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref> and made his debut for the club on 30 July 2008 in a friendly match against former team Arsenal. His competitive debut for the club came on 10 August 2008 in the first round of the [[DFB-Pokal]], a 5\u20130 away victory over [[FC Hansa L\u00fcneburg]], and his Bundesliga debut one week later in Stuttgart's 3\u20131 away victory at [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]].\n\nOn 3 April 2009 Lehmann extended his contract at VfB Stuttgart until the summer of 2010<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vfb.de/archiv/en/aktuell/news/2008/30298.php |title=Lehmann signs one year extension |publisher=vfb.de |accessdate=21 February 2014 |date=3 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226111034/http://www.vfb.de/archiv/en/aktuell/news/2008/30298.php |archivedate=26 February 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and announced in August 2009 that he would retire on 30 June 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/sport/702/485132/text/ |title=Jetzt ist mein Zahn weg | trans-title = Now my tooth is gone |language=German |work=S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung |accessdate=12 January 2010 |date=23 August 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091028164119/http://www.sueddeutsche.de/sport/702/485132/text/ | archive-date = 28 October 2009 | url-status = dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Arsenal (2011)===\n\nOn 14 March 2011, German tabloid ''[[Bild]]'' reported that Lehmann was in talks to come out of retirement, due to an injury crisis at Arsenal leaving them with only one fit senior keeper, [[Manuel Almunia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bild.de/BILD/sport/fussball/international/2011/03/14/jens-lehmann/comeback-bei-arsenal-london.html |publisher=Bild.de |title=Jens Lehmann: Comeback bei Arsenal perfekt |language=German |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=14 March 2011}}</ref> Lehmann was also scheduled to spend six weeks working on his coaching badges at his old club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11670_6813392,00.html |title=Lehmann in Arsenal talks |publisher=Sky Sports |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=14 March 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110315203538/http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11670_6813392,00.html | archive-date = 15 March 2011 | url-status = dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Due to the injury of Arsenal goalkeepers [[Wojciech Szcz\u0119sny]], [[\u0141ukasz Fabia\u0144ski]] and [[Vito Mannone]], on 17 March 2011 Lehmann signed for Arsenal on a rolling contract until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/lehmann-rejoins-arsenal-on-short-term-deal |title=Lehmann rejoins Arsenal on short-term deal |publisher=Arsenal.com |accessdate=17 March 2011 |date=17 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701092937/http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/lehmann-rejoins-arsenal-on-short-term-deal |archivedate=1 July 2011 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Lehmann was named as a substitute in Arsenal's match against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 19 March 2011. Despite newspaper reports that he might replace Almunia, due to the Spanish's poor performances,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/mar/21/west-bromwich-albion-arsenal-premier-league |title=Jens Lehmann set to start after Arsenal lose ground at West Bromwich | access-date =26 March 2011 |work=The Guardian |date=21 March 2011 |first=Joe |last=Lovejoy}}</ref> Wenger admitted that Lehmann was not match fit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1368185/Arsene-Wenger-admits-Jens-Lehmann-isnt-fit-play-Arsenal.html |title=Wenger admits Lehmann isn't fit enough to answer Arsenal's goalkeeping problems |accessdate=26 March 2011 |work=Daily Mail |date=21 March 2011 |first=Sami |last=Mokbel}}</ref> Lehmann made his first appearance in [[Arsenal F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Arsenal's reserves]] on 29 March 2011 against Wigan, when Arsenal lost 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1371187/Jens-Lehmann-makes-shaky-start-second-Arsenal-career.html |title=Is this really the answer, Arsene? Shaky Lehmann lets in two on Arsenal comeback |first=Philip |last=Duncan |work=Daily Mail |accessdate=31 March 2011 |date=30 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April 2011, Lehmann started for the first team in an away game against [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]. He was forced to start the game when Almunia was injured in the warm up.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/9446285.stm |title=Blackpool 1\u20133 Arsenal |work=BBC Sport |date=10 April 2011 |accessdate=10 April 2011}}</ref> Winning 3\u20131, it was his 200th appearance for Arsenal. Lehmann became the oldest player to play for Arsenal in the Premier League but not the oldest to play for the Gunners in all competitions, a record held by [[Jock Rutherford]]. Lehmann's contract with Arsenal expired at the end of the season, and then he decided to retire once again.\n\nOn 8 September 2018, a match was organised between Arsenal legends and Real Madrid legends in which Lehmann appeared after [[David Seaman]] picked up injury during training. He eventually made two saves in the second half and then saved the shot from Alfonso during penalty shoot out. Arsenal legends won that match on penalties by 5\u20133 where Lehmann scored the last penalty for Arsenal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/arsenal-real-madrid-report-legends-13207643 |title=Arsenal legends 0-0 Real Madrid legends (5-3 pens): Jens Lehmann the hero in Gunners' penalty shootout victory |last=Smith |first=Alex |date=8 September 2018 |website=Mirror|access-date=8 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nLehmann made his debut for the [[Germany national football team|German national team]] against [[Oman national football team|Oman]] in February 1998 and earned 61 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for his country, 32 of which were friendlies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rsssf.com/miscellaneous/lehmann-intl.html |title=Jens Lehmann - International Appearances |first=Matthias |last=Arnhold |date=1 October 2015 |accessdate=12 November 2015 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation}}</ref>\n\nHe had a well-publicised rivalry with former [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] goalkeeper [[Oliver Kahn]], whose presence long prevented Lehmann from becoming the number one goalkeeper of the national team. Lehmann was in the squad  which finished as runners-up in the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], but he didn't play any matches in the competition, as Kahn was still Germany's first choice goalkeeper.\n\nOn 7 April 2006, however, German national coach [[J\u00fcrgen Klinsmann]] announced that Lehmann would be Germany's first-choice goalkeeper for the upcoming [[2006 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]]. Lehmann conceded two goals in Germany's opening match of the World Cup, both scored by [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica's]] [[Paulo Wanchope]] although Germany won the match 4\u20132. Lehmann played strongly in the next three games, conceding no goals and allowing Germany to sweep their group undefeated and beat Sweden convincingly in the Round of 16.\n\nThe highlight of Lehmann's international career came in the quarterfinal match (30 June 2006, Olympiastadion, Berlin) against Argentina. The game remained tied 1\u20131 after 90 minutes and extra time. The game came down to penalty kicks and Lehmann carried his team through, picking the right direction for all spot kicks, making saves from Argentinians [[Roberto Ayala]] and [[Esteban Cambiasso]] and almost saving a third. Meanwhile, the Germans made all four of the necessary spot kicks to win the penalty shoot-out 4\u20132. Lehmann's prowess in the shootout was aided by notes given to him before the kicks \u2013 an idea from Germany's chief scout, Swiss-born [[:de:Urs Siegenthaler|Urs Siegenthaler]] \u2013 with Lehmann keeping the paper in his right sock. Before the last shot from Cambiasso, Lehmann looked at the paper for a long time even though Cambiasso's name was not even on it. The story about the paper features in the film ''[[Deutschland. Ein Sommerm\u00e4rchen]]''. Lehmann was considered a hero by the German public after these saves, and he received praise even from long-time rival and backup keeper Oliver Kahn.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lehmann had penalty taker notes |work=BBC Sport |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2006/teams/germany/5136802.stm |accessdate=1 July 2006 |date=1 July 2006}}</ref>\n\nGermany's opponent in the semifinals was Italy. The Italians had the better chances to score but Lehmann made several spectacular saves, including one in extra time where he dived out of goal to intercept an Italian player who had broken loose from the defence, punching the ball clear with his fist and temporarily knocking out the Italian in the process. He allowed two goals within a minute of each other with only a few seconds remaining in extra time, which put Italy into the World Cup final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991640.stm |title=Germany 0-2 Italy (aet) |work=BBC Sport |date=4 July 2006 |accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref> The retiring Oliver Kahn was given the honour of starting in the third place play-off match, an offer made by Lehmann himself. Kahn was made captain for that game due to the injury to [[Michael Ballack]]. Germany defeated Portugal 3\u20131 for the third place (bronze) medals.\n\nIn August 2006, Lehmann revealed that during the World Cup he was suffering with a foot injury that he claims was a result of wearing different boots. The [[German Football Association]] ordered their players to wear only those manufactured by principal sponsor [[Adidas]] as opposed to Lehmann's sponsor [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]. This has now been overturned thanks to Lehmann and several other players protesting about the decision and the players are now free to wear boots made by other companies.\n\nIn August 2006, Lehmann suggested that he may retire from league and international football after playing for Germany in [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Lehmann plans to retire after Euro 2008 |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=375850&cc=4716 |publisher=ESPNsoccernet |date=14 August 2006 |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> However, he subsequently stated in January 2007 that he had not made any decision on retirement.\n\nLehmann set a national team record of not conceding a goal for 681 minutes in a friendly against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] on 26 March 2008. In Euro 2008, Lehmann started every match as Germany reached the final. They lost 1\u20130 to Spain; a lack of communication between Lehmann and [[Philipp Lahm]] allowed Spain's [[Fernando Torres]] to net the only goal in the match.\n\nOn 8 August 2008, Lehmann announced his retirement from international football. He made his decision following a two-hour talk with the German national team's coach [[Joachim L\u00f6w]] and goalkeeping coach [[Andreas K\u00f6pke]], stating that he was not able to give them any guarantee that he will continue to play football following the end of his one-year contract with VfB Stuttgart in June 2009. He has since retired and subsequently worked towards his full FIFA coaching license at Arsenal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehardtackle.com/2013/draft123208/ |title=[Exclusive] Jens Lehmann \u2013 Arsenal Were Possibly The Best Ever Side On English Soil |first=Aditya |last=Balaram | website = The Hard Tackle |date=28 October 2013 |accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/news/newsid/228/049/5/ |title=Lehmann: Bayern are stronger than last year |publisher=FIFA |date=19 February 2014 |accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nAhead of the 2017\u201318 season, it was confirmed that Lehmann would return to Arsenal once again as assistant coach.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/arsenal/story/3153464/jens-lehmann-confirms-pending-appointment-as-arsenal-coach |website=ESPN FC |title=Jens Lehmann confirms pending appointment as Arsenal coach |date=5 July 2017}}</ref> On 19 June 2018, Arsenal confirmed that Lehmann had left the club as part of new head coach [[Unai Emery]]'s coaching staff changes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/first-team-coaching-staff-confirmed |title=First-team coaching staff confirmed |website=arsenal.com |date=19 June 2018 | access-date = 19 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January 2019, he was appointed assistant coach of [[FC Augsburg]] alongside [[Manuel Baum]], as the team is only 15th in the [[2018\u201319 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47036253 |title=Jens Lehmann: FC Augsburg appoint ex-Arsenal goalkeeper as assistant coach |date=29 January 2019 |work=BBC Sport | access-date = 29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLehmann and his elder brother grew up in [[Essen]]. After graduating from secondary school with [[A-levels]] ([[Abitur]]) in 1988, he studied [[Economics]] at the [[University of M\u00fcnster]] between 1992 and 1998 while continuing his football career.\n\nIn 1999, he married Conny, a middle school teacher. Lehmann later adopted Conny's son with footballer [[Knut Reinhardt]], [[Lasse Lehmann|Lasse]]. The pair also have two children Mats (born 2000) and Lieselotta (born 2006).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1763623/bio |title=Biography for Jens Lehmann |website=Internet Movie Database |accessdate=1 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Charity==\nHe is board member of the youth football foundation Stiftung Jugendfu\u00dfball, founded 2000 upon the initiative of [[J\u00fcrgen Klinsmann]]. Lehmann also acts as ambassador of the foundation Power-Child Campus South Africa<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.power-child-campus.com/en/start/aktuelles.php |title=News |publisher=power-child-campus.com |accessdate=1 December 2009 |date=4 June 2009}}</ref> that supports children affected by HIV and well as foundations of [[Bert Trautmann]], [[Christoph Metzelder]] and former Arsenal goalkeeper [[Bob Wilson (footballer, born 1941)|Bob Wilson]].\n\nHe participated in the [[Soccer Aid]] football match on 6 June 2010 for the Rest of the World team in aid of UNICEF.\n\n==Acting career==\nLehmann made his film acting debut with the German/South African production ''Themba''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thembathemovie.com/ |title=Themba |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref> He plays Big John Jacobs, a [[association football|football]] coach and [[talent scout]], who discovers Themba, a young and ambitious youth, who is faced with poverty, AIDS and violence, but eventually makes his way on to the [[South Africa national football team|South African national team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bz-berlin.de/sport/fussball/jens-lehmann-wird-film-schauspieler-article872398.html |title=Jens Lehmann wird Film-Schauspieler |work=Berliner Zeitung |accessdate=8 June 2010 |date=20 June 2010}}</ref> The movie is based on a novel by [[Lutz van Dijk]] and premiered at the [[Berlinale]] 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.germanyandafrica.diplo.de/Vertretung/pretoria__dz/en/__PR/2009__PR/05/05__Themba.html |title=German goalkeeper on the screen |publisher=germanyandafrica.diplo.de |accessdate=1 December 2009 |date=18 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n<ref name=\"NFT\">{{NFT player}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Club\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! colspan=\"3\" | League\n! colspan=\"2\" | Cup\n! colspan=\"2\" | League Cup\n! colspan=\"2\" | Europe\n! colspan=\"2\" | Other{{efn|Appearances in [[FA Community Shield]]}}\n! colspan=\"2\" | Total\n|-\n! Division\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"11\"|[[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]||[[1988\u201389 2. Bundesliga|1988\u201389]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[2. Bundesliga]]||13||0||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||16||0\n|-\n|[[1989\u201390 2. Bundesliga|1989\u201390]]||27||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||27||0\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 2. Bundesliga|1990\u201391]]||34||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||0\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 Bundesliga|1991\u201392]]||rowspan=\"7\"|[[Bundesliga]]||37||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||38||0\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 Bundesliga|1992\u201393]]||8||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||0\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 Bundesliga|1993\u201394]]||21||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||0\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 Bundesliga|1994\u201395]]||34||1||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||38||1\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 Bundesliga|1995\u201396]]||32||0||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014